{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778555911,"nonce":"+WsUfSbDDioRG8ga6OgmLXILEDE=","message":"**Training-methods finding: linear-tracker parameterisation does not decouple at standard training budgets (2026-05-11)**\n\nThe decoupling-acid-test MVP (`410d7ac`, child of `d448c9d`, phase `f695729`) trained a learned linear tracker (`u_t = u_ff(t) - K_t·e_t`) and a learned linear regulator (`u_t = -K_t·e_t`) on the f47abb1-winner cost (post-go powerlaw, no jerk). At 1000-batch warmup-only training on laptop CPU, the optimizer left `u_ff` at near-zero (~0.02) and the tracker collapsed onto the regulator solution. Both gave statistically identical Δv ≈ +1%/+3.5%/+6% at pert_scales 0.5/1.0/1.5, vs GRU baseline ~0.5%.\n\n**Cross-cutting takeaway for training methods**: a richer architectural parameterisation alone does NOT guarantee the optimizer discovers the decoupled solution. For decoupling-related training-method designs (anywhere a controller's parameterisation gives the optimizer a feedforward channel), expect that the optimizer may prefer a regulator-like collapsed solution unless the training regime actively rewards using the feedforward channel — e.g. via adversarial disturbance during training (option d in the d448c9d comment), warm-starting from analytical feedforward, or longer training horizons.\n\nThis is not a tier shift — no method enters or leaves a class — but it's an important constraint for future decoupling-flavoured architecture designs and adversary couplings. Full discussion: `410d7ac`.","files":null}]}